<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900516-0010</DOCNO><DOCID>900516-0010.</DOCID><HL>   Circle K Corp.   Asks Protection   Of Chapter II   ---   Move Follows the Refusal   Of Creditors to Agree   To Junk Restructuring   ----   By Sonia L. Nazario   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>05/16/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3</SO><CO>   CKP</CO><IN>FOOD RETAILERS AND WHOLESALERS, CONVENIENCE STORES (FDR)BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)</IN><LP>   Circle K Corp., the nation's second-largest conveniencestore chain, filed for bankruptcy court protection last nightafter failing to get creditors to agree to a restructuring ofits $1.1 billion in high-yield, below-investment-grade &quot;junk&quot;debt.   Circle K President Robert A. Dearth Jr. told Circle Kemployees that management will continue to run the chain,based in Phoenix, Ariz., and that it is contacting keyvendors, seeking their cooperation to keep stores stocked.</LP><TEXT>   The filing under Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Codemarks the end of a hard-fought battle by William Franke andother outside directors to win lender approval of a plan toavoid a bankruptcy-law filing. The efforts were supported byCircle K's largest shareholder, the Cincinnati investor CarlLindner, whose American Financial Corp. holds 38% of thestock and is a large Circle K creditor. The moves were aimedat gaining enough time to sell assets, generate cash, anddesign a new competitive plan.   Indeed, the company last month averted a default on itsdebt by signing a preliminary accord with senior creditorsand Mr. Lindner that provided a seven-month moratorium ondebt and interest payments. And earlier this month, CircleK's widely criticized chairman, Karl Eller, resigned.</TEXT></DOC>